Try this:

    db.getCollection(&#39;some_collection&#39;).aggregate([
     { $sort: {&#39;executionDate&#39;: -1}},
     { $group: { &#39;_id&#39;: &#39;$commandName&#39;, &#39;doc&#39;: {$first: &#39;$$ROOT&#39;} } }
    ])

I believe this will result in what you&#39;re looking for: 

    db.collection.aggregate([
      {
        $group: {
          &quot;_id&quot;: &quot;$commandName&quot;,
          &quot;executionDate&quot;: {
            &quot;$last&quot;: &quot;$executionDate&quot;
          }
        }
      }
    ])

You can check it out [here][1]

Of course, if you want to match your expected output exactly, you can add a sort (this may not be necessary since your goal is to simply return the newest document from each group):

    {
     $sort: {
      &quot;executionDate&quot;: 1
     }
    }

You can check this version out [here.][2]


  [1]: https://mongoplayground.net/p/c1YkMu1aivV
  [2]: https://mongoplayground.net/p/BAnzAi9rzI6

The use-case the question presents is nearly covered in the [**`$last`**](https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/last/) **aggregation** operator documentation.

**Which summarises:**

&gt; the `$group` stage should follow a `$sort` stage to have the input
&gt; documents in a defined order. Since `$last` simply picks the last
&gt; document from a group.

**Query:** [Link](https://mongoplayground.net/p/yWsNUa3OaYC)

    db.collection.aggregate([
      {
        $sort: {
          executionDate: 1
        }
      },
      {
        $group: {
          _id: &quot;$commandName&quot;,
          executionDate: {
            $last: &quot;$executionDate&quot;
          }
        }
      }
    ]);

